webpackJsonp([0xbfddffeecd5c],{1472:function(e,t){e.exports={data:{tweetsJson:{from:"Emily Webber",date:"27 Mar 2015",tags:"#agile #lean",text:"Crisp's Blog » A Scrum Product Owner Checklist",searchResults:[{title:"Crisp's Blog » A Scrum Product Owner Checklist as a mind map",href:"https://blog.crisp.se/2015/03/27/hansbrattberg/a-scrum-product-owner-checklist",description:"27 Mar 2015 ... If you wonder what a Scrum Product Owner need to do, here's the checklist (in \nform of a mind map) for you! Here it is, A Scrum Product Owner Checklist as a pdf \nupdated 2015-03-27. PO_checklist. Maybe you've just been assigned the role \nScrum Product Owner, and you are thinking “what is required of me” ..."},{title:"A Scrum Product Owner Checklist as a pdf - Crisp's Blog",href:"https://blog.crisp.se/wp-content/uploads/2015/03/PO_checklist.pdf",description:"Product Owner. Checklist. Kickstart a new product or Epic. Create a Vision \ntogether with the team, stakeholders and customers. Lean Canvas. Vision Board. \nDefine MVP and break down to multiple releases. Validation Board. Create an \nInitial Feature list. You could try... Personas. Story Maps. Design Studio. Impact \nMapping."},{title:"Crisp's Blog » product-owner",href:"https://blog.crisp.se/tag/product-owner",description:"In Scrum, there is no “business analyst” role. In fact, there is not an explicit role for \ntester, project manager, architect, developer, data administrator, user experience \ndesigner, customer support representative, or product trainer. Instead, Scrum has \nthree roles: the product owner, the Scrum Master, and the delivery team."}],index:86}},pathContext:{index:86}}}});
